fields.Title: Visual consuming spaces outside our windows
fields.Description:
Our visual consumption of outdoor space has evolved during the current lock-down. _Never have I looked out the window so much._
 
From the confines of interiors, the windows we peer through and surrounding structures dictate the limits of what we see. 
_I wish my window was bigger._

These spaces overlap and extend beyond physically demarcated ‘blocks’ and neighborhoods. Each space perceived differently among New Yorkers.
_Can you see what I see?_
_Does it look better from there?_

fields.Title: Studiomates, quarantine edition
fields.Description: “studiomates: quarantine edition” is a set of portraits + interviews taken during quarantine. through this project we hoped to discover aspects about our studiomates that are undiscovered in the usual studio environment.

fields.Title: Social-Distancing Essentials at Home
fields.Description: This drawing explores the essential elements in two homes, diagramming only what is necessary for physical and/or emotional health and safety.

fields.Title: Every Day I'm Shuffling
fields.Description: This image shows the evolution of my improvised home office through the quarantine days. Changing the tables meant a new experience every time - always trying to shuffle my limited possibilities within the apartment.

fields.Title: Quarantine "Makeover"

fields.Title: Bellydancing Across Borders
fields.Description: Each Saturday, my mom hosts a bellydancing class via Facebook live. I, along with many of our family and friends, dance along across different time zones. Let's dance!

fields.Title: Moodscapes
fields.Description: Every morning for a week, I chose a parametric design tutorial (one of more than 100,000 from youtube), and watched the video at double-speed with no sound to mimic the stress I feel thinking about politics or summer internships. Then, using only the quick notes taken from the video, I tried to apply the content to a scene and render it, all in less than one hour. The results are several moods, and they capture the uncertainty of medium (online learning) and the time period.

fields.Title: Day In, Day In
fields.Description: Using my own home as the subject of drawing, Day In Day In illustrates one reality of so many makeshift workspaces during this quarantine period. Masks fitted on a 6'x6' grid represent the rigidity and emptiness of public space, juxtaposed to the looseness and messiness of the domestic environment where we now spend all of our time, day in and day out (but in).

fields.Title: Shattered Realities
fields.Description: Within a few weeks, realities that we took for granted were shattered by the new reality of COVID-19. Realities like restaurants, campus sunny days, studio, reviews, friends, etc.

One hundred fifty-eight minutes in five seconds. Climactic stills from films watched to pass the quarantine hours were sketched. The drawings were then animated to provide context for the moment: in this case, to reveal the thorns in a supposed triumph.

fields.Title: I see Dead Men Walking

fields.Title: Madness escaping my brain filters
fields.Description:
Being alone in isolation, it's hard to not have really weird thoughts. They grow exponentially weird as time goes by.

fields.Title: Topography Exercise
fields.Description: I thought it might be interesting to trace over a crumpled piece of paper as other people in the class have done. When I was going over the piece of paper with a pencil, the ridges and crumples reminded me of topographical elevations. So, using watercolors I used the folds and edges to come up with an imagined landscape. My favorite part about it is when you look at the piece of paper from the side the folds look like small mountains.

fields.Title: Virtual windows
fields.Description: These drawings look at how media shifts toward a heavier reliance on virtual platforms during quarantine. They question what we are imagining outside the "windows" - the goggles from domestic to outer world.

fields.Title: New York City Without Ground----Post Quarantine New Normal
fields.Description: Inspired by the phenomenon that more and more underused urban spaces are getting reoccupied and activated by the public due to the quarantine, such as the rooftops and fire escapes that are becoming new social spaces. The drawing then, reimagines New York City as a city without ground where people do not go downstairs anymore, but upwards to a new piece of landscape hovering above the existing NYC. The new urban landscape is shaped as the American flag pattern indicating a more united nation. The existing rooftops of the city are turned into fish farms----a blue carpet, where people on top could fish and produce food. The red tone of the landscape above, together with the blue of the existing, constitutes the colors of the nation. It is a collaboration not only between individuals, but between old and new that rely on each other closely. It is a potential Utopian future responding to Governor Cuomo's "in hope of a new normal".

fields.Title: CHECK YOUR SURROUNDINGS
fields.Description:
CHECK YOUR SURROUNDINGS is an exploratory film / performance piece that seeks to question visibility, performance, and awareness in regards to cameras. Through the banality, violence, and spectacle present at filmed events, I seek to explore these qualities through three parts: first by me dancing for my car's rear-view mirror, second using B'Tselem Camera Project's instances of camera confrontation, and lastly, through the world of cam girls.

Who is being filmed? Who wants to be filmed? Who knows they're being filmed? Am I the camera's target? Is the camera my target? The camera is a lure. The camera is a weapon. The camera may or may not be seen while in action. Who or what regulates the camera's visibility? Our own visibility?

Attached image shows a typology of three levels of control over our meals by displaying three individuals' life over the past two weeks. Each individual's  freedom over food is somehow defined by  policies of each city due to the varying conditions of  Covid-19 .

fields.Title: Stay Sane : Postcards
fields.Description: Developed during COVID-19 pandemic as a reaction to social distancing, the Stay Sane project experiments with information exchange at varying scales of time, collaboration, and mediums. At a one on one scale, the postcard communication is about sharing weekly themed observations with one other person via hand-drawn data delivered through the postal service. In a world where hyper speed exchange of information is essential and expected, Stay Sane reflects on these notions and gives time to communication to be received a couple of days (or even years) later...

fields.Title: Unmake2d
fields.Description:
As quarantine days pass, I start to notice the little things in my apartment that can make or break my mental being. A stain speck in my working table would normally not bother me since I had no time to handle the small stuff in my house while there are more pressing issues that I had to do outside from my home, such as going to classes, laser cut deadlines, or even just hanging-out. Nowadays with such outside-home issues no longer existent, that speck might as well be a rabid fire burning down my gas stove, my maple wooden cutting board, and my 5$ pepperoni pizza. 

Such irksome details are now also apparent in my virtual world, an entire universe of people, entertainment, and work that all exists in my 15-inch LED screen. Cleaning my desktop is now my habit, and tinkering with Rhinoceros is now my lifestyle, like a fighter plane mechanic making sure all of the jet's bolts are intact, doing stress tests to make sure the absolute maximum maneuverability when a dog-fight or a mission occurs.  

I recently discovered that the Rhinoceros unit tolerance determines the quality of make2d. Finally I have found an answer to a problem I've tackled with throughout my architectural education: why is make2d evil? In truth now I know that make2d isn't evil but is just misunderstood. All of those lines that took hours to clean was actually fixable just by typing an additional '0' on the unit tolerance setting. I have now found nirvana, I can make2d in peace. 

This graph shows how higher tolerance effects the mental happiness level of myself. Paradoxically though, I could only find such knowledge after weeks of isolation and deteriorating mental state. So have I finally won over Make2d? Or have I never had a chance?

fields.Title: Virtual Anxiety
fields.Description: How I experience digital anxiety in quarantine  days.

fields.Title: E-Scape City
fields.Description: My fifth stage interpretation of the collaborative manipulation session with DETAILS-19.  The drawing first incorporates each stage into cube then grasshopper to image trace and generate curves.   Points are extracted from each curve and projected vectors according to the geometric angles that appeared in the third stage of the collaboration.  The result are peaks and valleys evoking a dreamlike floating cityscape inspired by the futurist depictions in the fourth stage.

fields.Title: Social Distancing at Home / Virtual Gathering at Animal Crossing
fields.Description: This work aims to describe a phenomenom that the modern technology (the game of Animal Crossing) offers another form of gather at the time of social quarantine. It describes the juxtaposition of virtual space and physical space.

fields.Title: Stay Sane : Virtual Time Capsule
fields.Description: Developed during COVID-19 pandemic as a reaction to social distancing, the Stay Sane project experiments with information exchange at varying scales of time, collaboration, and mediums. At a collaborative scale, the virtual time capsule (locked until 2022) encourages a wider audience to submit thoughts, feelings, observations, desires,etc. In a world where hyper speed exchange of information is essential and expected, Stay Sane reflects on these notions and gives time for communication to be received a couple of days (or even years) later…

fields.Title: Warped
fields.Description: An overlay of how many steps I took (or my phone thought I took) each day from Feb 15 to Apr 15 with a visualization of my perception of time during this period.

fields.Title: Covid-19 enters the virtual realm
fields.Description: The drawings imagine what would happen if the hygienic effects of the pandemic become part of our daily lives where masks become part of our body. Wearing masks becomes so ingrained that even illustrations of people now include masks.

fields.Title: Time Squarantine
fields.Description: Time Square is one of the most visited places in New York and after the lock down it became a place of isolation. With this collage I tried to re imagine Time Square after the COVID-19 spread in the city. I replaced the commercial ads with images related to the pandemic and the regular crowd with people in hazmat suits.

fields.Title: Life (In Quarantine)
fields.Description: This work evaluates the way in which our environment is reoriented in quarantine. It considers the way in which, without our shared environments, home environments have become more dynamic.

fields.Title: Diary of a Finals Bound Architecture Student
fields.Description: In the days leading up to final crit, I decided to track both my stream of thoughts as well as my overall confidence in my project. Every 30 minutes, I was to jot down the first thing which came to my mind and plot on a scale from  "spectacular!" to "sh\*t I'm f\*cked" my overall mood/optimism.

fields.Title: A Day of Co-Existing Quarantine
fields.Description: A typical day schedule of me quarantining in a hotel and my brother quarantining at home. Our virtual interactions significantly changed/increased after we've travelled back to the same time zone. We roughly recorded what we were doing every half an hour. The two activities that brought us together virtually were messaging/video-calling and gaming on PUBG mobile. It was also interesting to see times when we were unconsciously doing the same activities but at different locations.

fields.Title: GSAPP-Craft

The project was created before the formation of LionCraft (a campus-wide minecraft project), but has since been uploaded to the LionCraft Server. Visit it at **35.185.21.86**

fields.Title: Earth Cakes
fields.Description: Nature is no longer associated with mountain and forest with lake, islands and beaches. It has become more fragmented, National Parks, polluted plants, ruins.. like commodities, like cakes.

fields.Title: Surreality of Telemedicine
fields.Description: This collage aims to describe surreal experiences of telemedicine: communicating with a doctor only over the phone not knowing how he/she looks like; receiving medical devices and medicines in the envelope pinned on the wall outside the medical center; measuring body temperature, oxygen saturation etc by yourself and reporting back to the doctor; and being told that most likely you got Covid-19.

fields.Title: Alphabet City
fields.Description: This typeface, made from aerial photographs of apartment buildings (and some monuments) in Manhattan, reminds people of the necessity to shelter at home during the public health emergency. Playful, informative, and inspired by other political typefaces like Gerry - the font from Gerrymandered districts - Alphabet City insists on relocating physical space to convey information in a novel way.

fields.Title: Jordan's Workspace- Line Drawing
fields.Description: Part I of a collaboration with Jordan Readyhough. Drawing is entirely based off of a written description of Jordan's workspace.

fields.Title: GIFing The News
fields.Description:
As we're in isolation, the single common denominator in our individual experiences  during this unique time is the daily news that is delivered to us by the public representatives that are at the helm of our collective response to this crisis. Following the prompt 'Collaboration', we decided to examine coexistence and community in the broader social spectrum via telepresence in the Pandemic Present. 

Each frame in the GIFs is a screenshot taken at 5 minute intervals over the first half hour of the daily briefing held by these elected officials on the 25th day of the Pause.

fields.Title: Solitary & Collective
fields.Description:
The shading in cone shape represents our domestic space
The canvas is our public realm
In confinement, the gregarious people long for the collective platform
While in collective people retreat in their solitary and personal spaces
The ongoing struggle between the solitary and collective

fields.Title: Daily Routine
fields.Description: Doing our daily routine but from a distance.  An exploration into space and boundaries.

fields.Title: Musical Treadmills
fields.Description:
This drawing was not originally completed for spatial quaranzine, but upon looking at it with freshly-quarantined eyes, it also kind of serves as a diagram for spread of contagion the longer people spend on treadmills (the more they exhale.)
Original Description:
This is a drawing of a typical day on the third floor of the Tri-Level Fitness Area in the Dodge Fitness Center at Columbia University. Use of the cardio machines is regulated by a sign-up sheet split up into 30-minute increments. This drawing is a documentation of the incredible collective movement that happens in each of these sets and the churn in between each.

fields.Title: Tangible Thoughts
fields.Description: I have always lived in my mind thinking of all the fleeting lived moments that flash through my eyes. Ideas, memories, nostalgia, that is all good in moderation, right? This time around the year, more than ever, I experience this with more intensity due to covid-19 quarantine. I find myself struggling every day to get out of the thoughts that sporadically make me sad, happy, anxious or all together. In  this room representation I wanted to illustrate myself in my small bedroom, where I spend most of the time sleeping or trying to be creative in front of my desk. Each extruded mass from the wall represents my mind collecting multiple thoughts during the day, almost invading me while I try to get through this pandemic as best as I can. How busy would your room look if your thoughts were tangible?

fields.Title: Dream Subway System
fields.Description: Using the Brand New Subway website,<http://jpw.nyc/subway/>, Ally and Andrew both created their dream subway system, and then tried to express that system in a set of goals for the other person to create. **Ally’s** prioritized parks, Architecture, and Neighborhood collaboration, and **Andrew **prioritized cross-connections, visitor-experience, and ease-of-access. The resulting GIFs compare the ideal subway map with the other participant's interpretation, and show how difficult it can be to convey complex data-driven information in a visual format.
